                    <item>
              <title>Integrating Student experience into learning - APEL</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/729</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/729</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>
We are currently in the process of developing 'supported APEL' routes for our new 60 point courses. These are in fact shortened versions of the 'parent' course with some tutor support, teaching materials and formative assessment. However, we now wonder if there are other more appropriate and efficient ways of recognising prior experience - so that we connect with students' individual needs and make sure that they enter programmes at the best possible place. 
</p>
<p>
&nbsp;
</p>
<p>
For example we might have a 'starter' assessment course which acts as a diagnostic to suggest where within the rest of the award students might start. This may also mean that courses (modules?) need to be offered in smaller chunks - say 10 or 15 points. This could still be within a 60 point framework if we wished. 
</p>
<p>
&nbsp;
</p>
<p>
&nbsp;
</p>
]]></description>
          <pubDate>Thu, 15 Jan 2009 14:22:23 +0000</pubDate>
