              <title>The context for design across courses at Sydney</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/630</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/630</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>
<strong>Three parts</strong>:
</p>
<ul>
	<li>Context of e-learning at Sydney</li>
	<li>Cycles of design</li>
	<li>Barriers to teaching as design</li>
	<li></li>
</ul>
<p>
&nbsp;
</p>
<p>
<strong>Overarching questions<br />
</strong>
</p>
<ul>
	<li>Will universities ever be configured to use this stuff – ie tools and design ideas?</li>
	<li>Particularly in a campus based and research intensive university?</li>
	<li>Idea of researcher as teacher – what are the markers of professional identity</li>
	<li>Go write a paper, teach what you research, NOT design what you teach</li>
	<li>Size is an issue – Sydney is a large institution</li>
</ul>
<p>
<br />
<strong>Cycles of design in relation to ICTs</strong>
</p>
<ul>
	<li>Avoidance ca. 40% - too busy, not relevant, no money, no support</li>
	<li>Toe in the water ca. 40% little above information based and minor changes</li>
	<li>Committed approaches to integrated designs</li>
	<li>Barrier to greater uptake are complex</li>
</ul>
<p>
<br />
<strong>Barriers to growth</strong>
</p>
<ul>
	<li>Markers of a legitimate professional identity of teacher/designers (with ICTs) – workload recognition for design, budgets for online tutoring, teaching category of online tutoring,</li>
	<li>Shared design language – linking shared deign language to use of tools for even the technophobic or just slight irritated</li>
</ul>
<p>
<br />
<strong>How do we overcome the barriers?</strong>
</p>
<ul>
	<li>Better tools?</li>
	<li>Executive buy-in?</li>
	<li>Faculty demand?</li>
	<li>Student demand?</li>
	<li>Transparent design language?<br />
	</li>
</ul>
]]></description>
          <pubDate>Wed, 10 Dec 2008 04:08:17 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Views from learning and teaching in HE</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/629</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/629</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>
<strong>Views from learning and teaching in HE  – some reflections from those with particular expertise in managing and evaluating strategies</strong> <strong>for the enhancement of learning and teaching in HE</strong><br />
<br />
1.    Some questions – apply theoretical perspective to very concrete applications<br />
2.    Teaching as design and changing nature of HE context<br />
3.    Personal change strategies and identities – how and why people might change their practices<br />
<br />
Comment by Peter Goodyear – we need an ethnographic awareness of teachers’ context, its about social context and current social practices and where innovations are introduced and understand how they impact on practice. Constellations, orders of meaning, identity, power relationships
</p>
<p>
&nbsp;
</p>
<p>
<strong>Questions – developing an anthropological lens<br />
</strong>
</p>
<ul>
	<li>How do the new practices relate to current social practices?</li>
	<li>What practices are we expecting people to engage in and how do they relate?</li>
	<li>What codes of signification are evoked by what is being offered?</li>
	<li>What discourse are we using and what are teachers using?</li>
	<li>Power relations – what does it do for teacher autonomy, professionalism etc?</li>
	<li>What are teachers tacit theories?</li>
	<li>Can you leave room for ‘domestification’ – shaping to current practice, domesticating a new technology?</li>
	<li>Who are the users and where are the cultural boundaries?</li>
	<li>Where is the profitability for users and more importantly how can you show them the benefits?</li>
	<li>What is a reasonable vision for the tools we are developing in terms of scaling up – do you want everyone to use it?</li>
	<li>What are our theories for change?</li>
	<li>Discourses of the field give a number of metaphors</li>
	<li>Gift metaphor – offering – need and want</li>
	<li>Marketing metaphor – the product</li>
	<li>Requiring metaphor, co-creating – this is our tool, driver of compliance and sharing</li>
</ul>
<p>
<br />
Impetus for a more purposive approach to the construction of learning moments, its time has come. Chronic factors are how to create interesting, challenging learning environment for learners, this has been a problem for a long time, coupled with a policy drive and transparency/accountability. <br />
<br />
<strong>Three axes of consideration thinking about teaching and teachers as designers</strong>
</p>
<ul>
	<li>1st axes – policy and professional context. In the UK there is a performative impetrative in HE, foregrounding of it as a set of public practices, teachers are having to talk about what they do and why they do it, students are having to pay for HE process, governments are questioning how much money should be distributed to HE. There is a transparency and accountability thrust. The panoptic – being watched, fears of deskilling, being watched etc – i.e. there are negative imperatives about this as well in terms of teacher perspective.</li>
	<li>2nd axes – the basis on which colleagues in HE might be prepared to change. Drawn from empirical data from evaluation studies around various EU projects. Teachers have embedded theories about change and on what basis they would change. What kind of zeitgeist or frame of mind do teachers need to be in to take this change on board?</li>
	<li>3rd axes – engagement strategies. On what basis would teachers be prepared to take these new opportunities on board. Palette EU project http://palette.ercim.org/ – set of different CoP applying a participatory design methodology (PDM). People found it hard to understand what PDM was, even though they signed up to the rhetoric. Continuum – developers, teachers and learners (and other boundary brokers between these). Notion was that they would be co-constructors of design solutions. At the other end of the spectrum was the one-dimensional notion of a client and developer, little discourse between them. PDM is a really powerful and important approach.</li>
</ul>
<p>
<br />
<br />
<strong>Personal change theories</strong><br />
This is reflected in the personal change theories Saunders et al have developed. First is a practice-based exemplar. People catch an interesting idea/embodiment and will begin to apply this. The problem is that is a weak theory of change as we don’t know who will take this up and when. There is no theory of engagement. More about them catching it by osmosis. Notion of a demonstrator, a pilot etc. Second is idea of resource dependency. Is strongest way to enact change is attached funding to it. Invite bids against a change programme. Quite a good theory. Third one is the idea of rhetorical support. Need a strong vision statement at a senior level to make it happen. Fourth one, which is one of strongest theories of change. Professional imperative. Looking for interesting and high quality teaching solutions for your learners, which is core to what professional teaching practice should be about. Fifth – to do with technological determinism. Three possible theories. 1. Global marketing – an institution has to engage with new technologies from a competitive perspective and also using the technologies to market their course as well. 2. Students expect the new technologies to be used. Push from student expectation. 3. Affordances of the technologies – what the technologies actually offer. Change in embedded in the technologies. The environment is transformed by them. <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
</p>
]]></description>
          <pubDate>Wed, 10 Dec 2008 03:36:19 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Learning, mediating technologies and the social memory</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/628</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/628</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>
Website: www.ufn.gu.se
</p>
<p>
&nbsp;
</p>
<p>
<strong>Research topics<br />
</strong>
</p>
<ul>
	<li>Interest in learning and how knowledge and information are organised in complex societies</li>
	<li>The role of digital media in transforming how information is stored accessed and made use of</li>
	<li>The role of new media ecology</li>
	<li>Empirically orientated with studies in schools universities work place etc</li>
	<li>Theoretical applied and developmental interests</li>
	<li>Methodological developments</li>
	<li>Ambition to combine macro and micro studies</li>
</ul>
<p>
<br />
<strong>Current research projects include<br />
</strong>
</p>
<ul>
	<li>Learning literacies and media</li>
	<li>Learning in the context of digital media and new media as resources for learning</li>
	<li>Classroom discourses and the social organisation of learning</li>
	<li></li>
</ul>
<p>
&nbsp;
</p>
<p>
<strong>Projects include<br />
</strong>
</p>
<ul>
	<li>LINT Interdaction and the development narrative knowing and remembering</li>
	<li>Learning to support in the work place</li>
	<li>Transforming information into knowledge</li>
	<li>Learning how to reason and argue</li>
	<li>Heteroglossia in the process of learning</li>
	<li>Mediational means in written academic discourse</li>
</ul>
<p>
<br />
<strong>Conceptual background</strong>
</p>
<ul>
	<li>An interest in the social and interactive shaping of minds</li>
	<li>Semiotic mediation and division of cognitive labour between minds and intellectual tools and artefacts</li>
	<li>Forms of appropriation</li>
	<li>The building up of social memory in complex society</li>
</ul>
<p>
(Dewey social experiences)<br />
<br />
Learning/social remembering in a sociocultural and pragmatist perspectives<br />
1. How individuals, organisations and society at large retain information, knowledge and skills, transform them and make them available to new generations<br />
2. The issue of how people come to share the experiences of their society the funded capital of socialisation (Dewey) through various forms of communication and social activities<br />
<br />
Evolutionary ladder of technologies <br />
1.    ABC, ruin stones, other technologies that new generations<br />
<br />
A key process in the development and expansion of human knowing and sharing of experiences is externalisation through the design of cultural tools <br />
<br />
Experiences converted into linguistic/discursive tools (such as concept, categorising practice, narratives, social languages) and material artefacts (technologies)<br />
<br />
The technology provides new forms of access to cultural knowledge, we master technologies as part of social practices without needed to know the details of the technologies themselves, transparency of the technologies give us access to very complex social practices<br />
<br />
External symbolic storages (ESS) – books, libraries, maps and charts, registers, clocks, databases, instruments - embodied practices<br />
Artificial memory systems (AMS)<br />
<br />
Cultural (or re-presentational) tools – inscriptions and processes of reification/fixation of meaning<br />
Externalisation or objectification of<br />
information (texts, spoken narratives, etc), <br />
also seeing now with technologies – externalisation of human thought processes (expansion of social memory through the technologies) <br />
<br />
<strong>Externalisation of cognitive functions</strong>
</p>
<ul>
	<li>Computer software – spell and grammar check, statistical analysis packages, etc</li>
	<li>Search engines</li>
	<li>Book keeping programmes</li>
	<li>Graphical and symbol manipulating calculators</li>
	<li>Navigators</li>
	<li>Face recognition devices</li>
	<li>Medical imaging technologies </li>
</ul>
<p>
<br />
Technologies come in as cultural and cognitive amplifiers and as access points to cultural knowing<br />
<br />
<strong>Transformations of learning</strong>
</p>
<ul>
	<li>We master complex tasks without understanding the sequential steps</li>
	<li>Technologies function as a black box (trust)</li>
	<li>We increasingly learne from the complex to the elementary</li>
	<li>We understand as part of practices we do not necessarily understand as part of the hierarchically organised knowledge such as the disciplines</li>
</ul>
<p>
<br />
Interpretatins of learning in a digital age<br />
Metacommunicative and meta cognitive skills (modelling)<br />
Learing becomes increasingly conceptual and procedural but in coordination with material cultural tools<br />
Learning is the ability to transform and recontextualise in manners that are relevant for local needs ie learning is in the performative
</p>
